1
00:00:07,659 --> 00:00:11,600
Hello and welcome to the Game Art Remastered panel,

2
00:00:11,900 --> 00:00:15,161
featuring Brian Sousa from Blizzard Entertainment

3
00:00:15,201 --> 00:00:16,442
talking about StarCraft Remastered,

4
00:00:17,242 --> 00:00:19,723
Corey from Vicarious Visions will be talking about Crash

5
00:00:19,783 --> 00:00:22,764
Bandicoot, and Eugene will be talking, oh, from Shiny Shoe

6
00:00:23,064 --> 00:00:24,364
will be talking about Full Throttle.

7
00:00:25,765 --> 00:00:29,886
I'm going to start this one off with StarCraft Remastered.

8
00:00:31,747 --> 00:00:33,247
There's a lot of questions people

9
00:00:33,307 --> 00:00:37,168
have about why we would remaster a game, for instance.

10
00:00:37,987 --> 00:00:39,067
Why would you remaster a game?

11
00:00:40,428 --> 00:00:41,289
I'll talk a little bit on that,

12
00:00:41,469 --> 00:00:43,330
and mostly about how we did it.

13
00:00:44,430 --> 00:00:46,031
And there we go.

14
00:00:47,312 --> 00:00:47,933
This is not working.

15
00:00:48,733 --> 00:00:49,093
There we go.

16
00:00:50,674 --> 00:00:52,015
So most of you probably don't remember

17
00:00:52,055 --> 00:00:54,056
the good old days of the 1990s.

18
00:00:54,717 --> 00:00:57,038
Blizzard had just hit two pretty successful games

19
00:00:57,058 --> 00:00:58,519
with Warcraft I and Warcraft II.

20
00:00:59,515 --> 00:01:02,015
And while we did think about other games that we could develop,

21
00:01:02,555 --> 00:01:04,576
another RTS was inevitable.

22
00:01:05,496 --> 00:01:08,416
What we did though is we switched genres altogether

23
00:01:08,616 --> 00:01:13,377
from fantasies to science fiction, and we added a third race.

24
00:01:13,817 --> 00:01:17,298
So we have the Stoic Terrans, the Enigmatic Protoss,

25
00:01:17,938 --> 00:01:19,238
and the Swarms of Zerg.

26
00:01:19,258 --> 00:01:21,879
A little bit about StarCraft.

27
00:01:22,119 --> 00:01:24,699
It was about a three-year development cycle.

28
00:01:25,159 --> 00:01:27,260
We took a little time off for Diablo, if you remember that.

29
00:01:28,272 --> 00:01:30,332
and it was released in the spring of 1998.

30
00:01:31,612 --> 00:01:33,012
Brood War was released later that year,

31
00:01:34,773 --> 00:01:36,733
and this was actually the formation

32
00:01:36,893 --> 00:01:38,513
of a dedicated cinematic team.

33
00:01:39,414 --> 00:01:41,474
I should know, I was there.

34
00:01:41,994 --> 00:01:44,734
I'm on the top row, still bald, still angry.

35
00:01:45,575 --> 00:01:46,755
Just kidding.

36
00:01:46,795 --> 00:01:51,036
20 years later, 20 pounds later, and that's me now.

37
00:01:52,556 --> 00:01:54,896
Blizzard has released many new games

38
00:01:55,176 --> 00:01:56,237
since StarCraft had come out.

39
00:01:58,777 --> 00:02:01,458
But the fact is that millions of people are still playing StarCraft 1.

40
00:02:02,798 --> 00:02:06,259
Hundreds of tournaments, professional tournaments, have been played.

41
00:02:07,540 --> 00:02:13,402
The players have recreated and reimagined our editors to create new maps.

42
00:02:14,082 --> 00:02:18,763
And they've even set up private servers so they could play games with matchmaking and ladders.

43
00:02:20,955 --> 00:02:24,478
This was a picture from Busan when we released the remaster,

44
00:02:24,698 --> 00:02:29,683
and around 30,000 people showed up for our announcement,

45
00:02:29,703 --> 00:02:33,266
that's not the announcement, the release of StarCraft Remastered.

46
00:02:34,727 --> 00:02:37,189
However, we felt that it is actually our duty

47
00:02:38,190 --> 00:02:40,733
to keep these games alive, keep them up to date

48
00:02:40,933 --> 00:02:42,915
and accessible to all of our players.

49
00:02:43,215 --> 00:02:46,518
And so, the Blizzard Classic Games team was formed.

50
00:02:47,363 --> 00:02:52,988
I came on the team about two years ago, and I was focusing mainly on StarCraft Remastered.

51
00:02:53,849 --> 00:02:58,473
I had worked on the original, so they felt that my expertise would be invaluable.

52
00:03:00,014 --> 00:03:03,917
StarCraft was released at 640x480 resolution.

53
00:03:04,698 --> 00:03:08,781
It had 256 color palette and an amazing 15 frames per second.

54
00:03:09,762 --> 00:03:14,767
But it did have 8-player multiplayer, and that is what helped StarCraft become what

55
00:03:14,787 --> 00:03:15,267
it is today.

56
00:03:17,090 --> 00:03:23,394
So when we look back at what we were going to do with bringing StarCraft into our current

57
00:03:23,434 --> 00:03:30,018
battle plan, battle platform I should say, of Battle.net, we talked to the community

58
00:03:31,059 --> 00:03:32,039
and the professional players.

59
00:03:32,460 --> 00:03:34,781
We said, hey, what would you like to see?

60
00:03:37,903 --> 00:03:38,703
What could we fix?

61
00:03:39,284 --> 00:03:40,444
There's bugs in the game still.

62
00:03:41,625 --> 00:03:42,646
And what changes could we make?

63
00:03:43,652 --> 00:03:47,975
Well, a lot of it we suspected, and a lot of it was surprising.

64
00:03:48,455 --> 00:03:51,558
For instance, we knew we shouldn't touch the gameplay.

65
00:03:52,058 --> 00:03:53,680
The game has been played for 20 years.

66
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:56,101
Everybody loves the game as it is.

67
00:03:56,682 --> 00:03:57,382
It's like chess.

68
00:03:57,723 --> 00:03:59,524
You can change the board, you can change the pieces,

69
00:03:59,564 --> 00:04:01,606
but don't change the rules or how it plays.

70
00:04:03,147 --> 00:04:04,268
Don't fix the bugs.

71
00:04:04,848 --> 00:04:06,930
The bugs are incorporated into the gameplay now,

72
00:04:07,110 --> 00:04:10,533
and these players require these bugs.

73
00:04:10,951 --> 00:04:13,732
They like these bugs, they know, and they work around these bugs,

74
00:04:13,772 --> 00:04:15,053
and that's what makes a master player.

75
00:04:16,654 --> 00:04:18,114
There was one bug we fixed, however.

76
00:04:19,595 --> 00:04:21,616
Early in the development, Mike Morheim came to us,

77
00:04:21,796 --> 00:04:25,518
and he mentioned that there was a bug in that he introduced back in 1997,

78
00:04:27,059 --> 00:04:31,221
and it was just an animation that played one frame out of order,

79
00:04:31,941 --> 00:04:32,922
and it really bugged him.

80
00:04:33,182 --> 00:04:36,043
And so we actually said, okay, we'll fix that bug for you.

81
00:04:36,163 --> 00:04:37,964
It doesn't have anything to do with gameplay. We're good.

82
00:04:39,672 --> 00:04:41,253
And don't change the look.

83
00:04:42,674 --> 00:04:44,196
This was kind of surprising to us.

84
00:04:44,876 --> 00:04:49,099
But the fact that StarCraft looked a certain way

85
00:04:50,020 --> 00:04:51,961
was really key to the players.

86
00:04:53,642 --> 00:04:57,805
So this led us to say, well, what can we do with the remaster?

87
00:04:58,766 --> 00:05:03,109
And my boss came to us, and he basically

88
00:05:03,169 --> 00:05:05,711
told us, don't screw it up.

89
00:05:06,974 --> 00:05:09,575
Because this game has been played for so long,

90
00:05:09,595 --> 00:05:11,756
so many people love this game, still playing this game,

91
00:05:12,176 --> 00:05:14,337
that anything we do, we can't screw it up,

92
00:05:15,458 --> 00:05:18,219
which also gives us a lot to work with.

93
00:05:19,480 --> 00:05:21,480
So we started thinking about what our options could be.

94
00:05:22,341 --> 00:05:23,161
What if we did this?

95
00:05:23,321 --> 00:05:26,263
Well, we want to bring it up to 4K resolution,

96
00:05:26,763 --> 00:05:28,263
future-proofing it so in 20 years

97
00:05:28,303 --> 00:05:30,084
we're not revisiting all of these assets again,

98
00:05:30,624 --> 00:05:31,185
redoing them.

99
00:05:32,045 --> 00:05:33,906
We put in 16 by 9 widescreen support.

100
00:05:35,212 --> 00:05:36,813
Integration into Battle.net was key.

101
00:05:36,853 --> 00:05:40,315
That brings you up into today's player base.

102
00:05:41,495 --> 00:05:43,977
Seamlessly playable with the standard version,

103
00:05:44,737 --> 00:05:47,839
which was a huge undertaking to make that possible.

104
00:05:49,379 --> 00:05:52,301
We wanted to put in new lighting, additional ramp

105
00:05:52,321 --> 00:05:54,902
directions, additional animation frames.

106
00:05:55,663 --> 00:05:58,544
And my personal, because I worked on the Cinemax,

107
00:05:58,584 --> 00:06:01,105
I really wanted to update them for today.

108
00:06:02,366 --> 00:06:04,767
However, not all of these were possible.

109
00:06:06,624 --> 00:06:08,185
But we were able to up-res the graphics.

110
00:06:08,745 --> 00:06:12,388
Problems were we had no original assets to work from.

111
00:06:13,408 --> 00:06:16,590
We found a CD that one of the artists had burned

112
00:06:16,610 --> 00:06:19,072
that had assets from early games,

113
00:06:19,152 --> 00:06:21,833
Diablo, Starcraft, Warcraft II,

114
00:06:22,574 --> 00:06:24,035
and I was able to find a few models.

115
00:06:24,595 --> 00:06:25,836
They didn't have any textures on them

116
00:06:26,576 --> 00:06:29,178
and they were very rough, to say the least.

117
00:06:31,315 --> 00:06:32,496
We didn't have any art tools.

118
00:06:32,877 --> 00:06:34,058
All of the tools were gone.

119
00:06:34,358 --> 00:06:35,859
So we had to rewrite the art tools.

120
00:06:36,159 --> 00:06:38,661
And basically what we did was we extracted

121
00:06:38,781 --> 00:06:42,104
all of the original assets and then scaled them up 400%

122
00:06:42,184 --> 00:06:44,446
to see what kind of resolution we're working with.

123
00:06:45,987 --> 00:06:47,148
And when we did this, we found out

124
00:06:47,168 --> 00:06:48,809
there's no consistent cameras or lighting.

125
00:06:49,430 --> 00:06:50,791
I don't know what those artists were thinking,

126
00:06:50,891 --> 00:06:53,513
but we had to eyeball everything to make sure

127
00:06:53,553 --> 00:06:56,095
that the perspective was right for the game

128
00:06:56,375 --> 00:06:58,136
and not right for what you would think.

129
00:07:00,070 --> 00:07:00,971
So what did we do?

130
00:07:01,071 --> 00:07:03,012
First, we said, let's get our style down.

131
00:07:04,312 --> 00:07:05,673
And we worked with the Battle Cruiser.

132
00:07:05,973 --> 00:07:09,335
The Battle Cruiser is big, it's badass, and it's iconic.

133
00:07:10,055 --> 00:07:11,296
Everybody knows the Battle Cruiser.

134
00:07:12,196 --> 00:07:13,257
So this is our first test.

135
00:07:13,277 --> 00:07:15,978
We set up a huge style guide about how we did it and what

136
00:07:15,998 --> 00:07:16,779
we were going for.

137
00:07:17,439 --> 00:07:21,921
And we showed these to our focus group.

138
00:07:22,682 --> 00:07:23,142
They hated it.

139
00:07:23,942 --> 00:07:24,783
It wasn't what they wanted.

140
00:07:25,282 --> 00:07:26,884
They already thought we were screwing up the game,

141
00:07:27,605 --> 00:07:30,070
and so we had to rethink.

142
00:07:30,791 --> 00:07:33,836
And so we came up with a second Battle Cruiser, which, as you

143
00:07:33,876 --> 00:07:35,318
can see, is more in line with the original.

144
00:07:36,700 --> 00:07:38,684
We went back then, and we looked at all of the original.

145
00:07:40,059 --> 00:07:45,161
uh... concepts uh... sam didi was awesome he kept everything he's ever drawn ever

146
00:07:45,661 --> 00:07:46,462
in these folders

147
00:07:47,022 --> 00:07:48,543
and so i got a lot of the stuff from him

148
00:07:49,143 --> 00:07:50,244
you can see the zergling had

149
00:07:50,664 --> 00:07:51,644
little arms on his back

150
00:07:52,245 --> 00:07:53,705
the ghost actually has six fingers

151
00:07:54,286 --> 00:07:54,846
which uh...

152
00:07:55,306 --> 00:07:56,987
i really forced into the game somehow

153
00:07:57,647 --> 00:07:58,328
you'll never see it

154
00:07:58,348 --> 00:07:58,388
uh...

155
00:08:01,029 --> 00:08:02,970
so this is what we did we took the original asset

156
00:08:03,838 --> 00:08:05,940
And then we did a concept of what kind of details

157
00:08:05,980 --> 00:08:07,221
we would add to this concept.

158
00:08:08,242 --> 00:08:09,243
Where could we go with this?

159
00:08:09,283 --> 00:08:11,085
Just kind of enhancing what was already there,

160
00:08:11,165 --> 00:08:12,125
just filling in the gaps.

161
00:08:12,906 --> 00:08:15,949
And then our final was rendered, and we built off

162
00:08:15,969 --> 00:08:18,211
of that final concept so that when you look at the game,

163
00:08:18,251 --> 00:08:20,353
you instantly recognize everything in it.

164
00:08:22,775 --> 00:08:23,376
Animations.

165
00:08:23,456 --> 00:08:25,097
This was one that we really wanted to do.

166
00:08:26,497 --> 00:08:29,118
If you look at StarCraft, the animations are very stiff.

167
00:08:29,138 --> 00:08:31,879
There's not very many frames for any of the things.

168
00:08:31,919 --> 00:08:34,200
Some of them have four or five frames for a complete cycle.

169
00:08:34,380 --> 00:08:36,000
And they're playing this at 15 frames a second.

170
00:08:36,120 --> 00:08:38,321
So they're just repeating frames over and over.

171
00:08:39,041 --> 00:08:42,863
We did a test with the Zealot of how it could be.

172
00:08:43,383 --> 00:08:44,964
We added a new idle frame.

173
00:08:45,384 --> 00:08:46,224
We added a new run.

174
00:08:48,144 --> 00:08:50,506
It turns out that this was a little bit too much,

175
00:08:50,566 --> 00:08:52,728
and it changed the game, the perception of the game,

176
00:08:52,768 --> 00:08:54,269
of how these units acted.

177
00:08:54,830 --> 00:08:56,711
Some of the professional players actually

178
00:08:56,771 --> 00:08:59,914
would recognize frame three of the Zergling's attack

179
00:08:59,974 --> 00:09:02,256
as when it does the damage, and then it can move it away.

180
00:09:02,776 --> 00:09:07,280
So we basically had to scrap our ideas of adding animation.

181
00:09:08,241 --> 00:09:12,985
And speaking of the Zergling, originally we had a man,

182
00:09:13,005 --> 00:09:14,546
and we had a play test.

183
00:09:16,407 --> 00:09:19,710
the professionals felt he felt too small. He was exactly the

184
00:09:19,750 --> 00:09:22,692
same size and it was all perception because we didn't

185
00:09:22,732 --> 00:09:27,456
change the hit test box at all. It's the same one from standard

186
00:09:28,117 --> 00:09:33,681
but because they felt it was smaller, they perceived it that

187
00:09:33,721 --> 00:09:37,585
way so we scaled it up a little bit just so they would have a

188
00:09:38,165 --> 00:09:41,748
easier time of it. We were also able to

189
00:09:43,070 --> 00:09:43,991
go through the angles.

190
00:09:44,731 --> 00:09:48,834
Originally the game was supposed to have 36, 32 angles?

191
00:09:49,395 --> 00:09:50,856
32 angles, yeah.

192
00:09:51,236 --> 00:09:52,977
But because of memory constraints at the time,

193
00:09:53,418 --> 00:09:56,460
it was cut down to only 16, which is only nine flipped.

194
00:09:57,381 --> 00:09:59,462
So frames one and two, exactly the same.

195
00:09:59,723 --> 00:10:00,964
Three and four, exactly the same.

196
00:10:01,124 --> 00:10:03,125
And we went in and we were able to put

197
00:10:03,165 --> 00:10:04,826
in more angles of rotation.

198
00:10:07,814 --> 00:10:10,377
One of the biggest changes we did was for the lighting.

199
00:10:10,958 --> 00:10:13,602
We have the standard in-game sprite,

200
00:10:13,862 --> 00:10:16,866
which matches almost one-to-one with the originals.

201
00:10:17,447 --> 00:10:20,170
However, we added a new lighting system.

202
00:10:21,105 --> 00:10:24,348
which adds ambient occlusion mapping, depth mapping,

203
00:10:24,608 --> 00:10:26,009
normal mapping, specular map.

204
00:10:26,410 --> 00:10:29,092
And this gives the actual, we have in-game lighting

205
00:10:29,132 --> 00:10:31,954
that can affect these to make it a little more depth,

206
00:10:32,114 --> 00:10:33,896
like a two and a half D representation.

207
00:10:34,456 --> 00:10:36,998
We were actually able to put lights onto units,

208
00:10:37,279 --> 00:10:38,320
and so they kind of glowed

209
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:39,420
and they would affect the buildings.

210
00:10:41,382 --> 00:10:44,144
And of course, we had to add widescreen support.

211
00:10:45,225 --> 00:10:47,187
Now, you would probably think this is not a big deal.

212
00:10:47,707 --> 00:10:48,888
Change the camera, you're good.

213
00:10:49,635 --> 00:10:51,435
The biggest problem was the consoles.

214
00:10:52,716 --> 00:10:54,116
And the consoles were a pain in the butt.

215
00:10:55,617 --> 00:10:57,617
We had to make them be expandable from 4 by 3

216
00:10:58,298 --> 00:10:58,978
to 16 by 9.

217
00:11:00,338 --> 00:11:03,960
And we worked on these consoles up until ship,

218
00:11:04,480 --> 00:11:07,081
until after ship with feedback from the community.

219
00:11:07,661 --> 00:11:10,902
Because they just weren't feeling right.

220
00:11:11,202 --> 00:11:12,603
So finally, we got something in.

221
00:11:13,043 --> 00:11:14,463
We had these expandable consoles.

222
00:11:14,883 --> 00:11:15,484
And I'm happy.

223
00:11:15,664 --> 00:11:16,484
We never have to do it again.

224
00:11:18,781 --> 00:11:19,522
The environments.

225
00:11:20,403 --> 00:11:22,665
As many of the units in the buildings as there were,

226
00:11:22,705 --> 00:11:25,147
there was eight environments that we had to do,

227
00:11:25,447 --> 00:11:27,509
each with thousands of individual cells.

228
00:11:28,010 --> 00:11:30,032
And each of these cells had to be put together

229
00:11:30,072 --> 00:11:30,853
like a puzzle piece.

230
00:11:31,473 --> 00:11:33,795
And we had no way of knowing how these things worked.

231
00:11:34,656 --> 00:11:36,398
We actually had to create documents,

232
00:11:36,918 --> 00:11:38,020
and we had the engineers

233
00:11:40,664 --> 00:11:43,425
extract all of the numbers so you could see them on screen,

234
00:11:43,926 --> 00:11:45,687
like which tile goes to which tile.

235
00:11:46,127 --> 00:11:48,129
And there's like just in the tile sets of numbers,

236
00:11:48,169 --> 00:11:50,750
there's 33,000 of these that we had to make sure

237
00:11:50,770 --> 00:11:51,631
that all fit together.

238
00:11:54,353 --> 00:11:56,114
And we did add some new water.

239
00:11:56,294 --> 00:11:57,955
The original water was color cycled,

240
00:11:59,036 --> 00:12:00,057
usually with five colors,

241
00:12:00,117 --> 00:12:01,358
and it just kind of rotated through them.

242
00:12:01,838 --> 00:12:04,240
And then we added a new shader to the water,

243
00:12:04,360 --> 00:12:06,501
and I think this was the biggest revamp

244
00:12:06,541 --> 00:12:07,762
for the actual graphics.

245
00:12:10,894 --> 00:12:16,975
the ramps. There was only two ramps in StarCraft, uh, Southwest and Southeast, which at the

246
00:12:17,015 --> 00:12:23,257
time seemed like it was okay, right? We didn't expect this to be a huge, um, tournament based

247
00:12:23,717 --> 00:12:29,698
game that's, you know, been played for 20 years. Um, the community stepped up again and

248
00:12:29,718 --> 00:12:35,939
they actually created in the world editor their own ramps using pieces that were already

249
00:12:35,979 --> 00:12:39,920
existing. Well, they were hard to make and they didn't actually fit in that well.

250
00:12:40,645 --> 00:12:44,047
So we took our time, and we put in all new directions.

251
00:12:44,067 --> 00:12:45,108
So we added six directions.

252
00:12:45,529 --> 00:12:47,310
And all of these are expandable, so you can make

253
00:12:47,430 --> 00:12:48,611
whatever size ramp you want.

254
