00:16:44,494 --> 00:16:46,255
Bowser and Crash into the Skylanders games.

329
00:16:48,036 --> 00:16:51,957
Doing this gave me some practical experience trying to meet the goals of a new and different

330
00:16:51,977 --> 00:16:55,359
product while being respectful of a brand's heritage.

331
00:16:56,760 --> 00:17:00,541
I personally think it's wise to recognize the meaning iconic franchise characters have

332
00:17:00,822 --> 00:17:02,062
to their audience and to their fans.

333
00:17:03,112 --> 00:17:07,815
My deck will focus on characters, but I hope to reflect the feelings and approach of our

334
00:17:07,995 --> 00:17:09,156
remaster project in general.

335
00:17:09,516 --> 00:17:14,300
And I feel this kind of work kind of begs you to yourself become a fan, which is a point

336
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:15,220
that I'll be returning to.

337
00:17:17,642 --> 00:17:18,843
So what were our broad goals?

338
00:17:19,723 --> 00:17:22,725
Our game is a from-scratch rebuild of the original three Crash games.

339
00:17:23,426 --> 00:17:28,109
A high-level overview of our approach is we wanted to represent the original games faithfully

340
00:17:28,990 --> 00:17:30,010
while building everything.

341
00:17:30,881 --> 00:17:32,161
from scratch, from the get-go.

342
00:17:33,022 --> 00:17:35,342
Both out of necessity, we didn't have access to everything,

343
00:17:35,903 --> 00:17:37,923
and a desire to achieve a modern presentation.

344
00:17:38,723 --> 00:17:41,504
In the end, we'd hope to kind of freshly reignite

345
00:17:41,524 --> 00:17:43,085
the love fans felt for the original

346
00:17:43,605 --> 00:17:45,866
by giving them something consistent with their memories,

347
00:17:46,606 --> 00:17:48,046
but also that felt visually modern.

348
00:17:50,127 --> 00:17:51,588
For characters, we wanted to bridge the gap

349
00:17:51,608 --> 00:17:55,249
between the classic 32-bit look of the original game

350
00:17:55,789 --> 00:17:57,750
and somewhat of a feature animation-type style.

351
00:17:58,829 --> 00:18:01,691
blend the low poly punch of like Naughty Dog's original art

352
00:18:02,452 --> 00:18:05,454
with modern expectations to find a kind of sweet spot

353
00:18:05,514 --> 00:18:06,774
of maximum nostalgia.

354
00:18:07,715 --> 00:18:09,716
Both of these things so as to hopefully not disappoint

355
00:18:09,757 --> 00:18:11,177
anyone playing it totally fresh

356
00:18:12,498 --> 00:18:13,799
or for the first time in two decades.

357
00:18:15,320 --> 00:18:16,641
And this could mean the usual things like

358
00:18:16,881 --> 00:18:19,423
more rounded out volumes, smoother deformations,

359
00:18:19,463 --> 00:18:20,684
more detailed texture presentation.

360
00:18:21,546 --> 00:18:25,891
But importantly, we couldn't sacrifice the essential design language

361
00:18:25,972 --> 00:18:28,435
that would be key to triggering those kind of fond feelings

362
00:18:28,475 --> 00:18:29,916
we wanted our audience to experience.

363
00:18:34,412 --> 00:18:37,635
There's two particular challenges that we've dealt with that I'd like to kind of focus on.

364
00:18:38,996 --> 00:18:43,820
Finding faithful designs for the rebuilt characters and supporting faithfully dynamic

365
00:18:43,860 --> 00:18:48,084
performances for them. Because we were rebuilding these games from scratch, part of the

366
00:18:48,104 --> 00:18:54,749
question becomes, where do we pull our style and inspiration from? This can kind of become a

367
00:18:54,770 --> 00:18:59,153
dilemma. It could be easy to go down the path into a full remake or reimagining territory.

368
00:19:00,817 --> 00:19:04,725
where changes that are not carefully executed could lead fans to question the intent of a

369
00:19:04,785 --> 00:19:06,549
product of a game like ours.

370
00:19:07,629 --> 00:19:14,112
Now, as a personal example, I, you know, remember as a kid watching cartoons, I would often

371
00:19:14,172 --> 00:19:18,655
wonder why characters would look off-model from like their 16-bit kind of representations

372
00:19:18,915 --> 00:19:20,276
if I was watching a video game cartoon.

373
00:19:20,856 --> 00:19:24,438
You know, and, you know, that's a harmless effect of graphical limitations at the time.

374
00:19:25,058 --> 00:19:29,000
But the point is, like, that we would want to try to avoid evoking that kind of disconnect

375
00:19:29,541 --> 00:19:33,183
with what we were making, that we wanted people to feel comfortable that what they were looking

376
00:19:33,303 --> 00:19:35,464
at is what they remembered and what they cared about.

377
00:19:38,707 --> 00:19:41,988
Because we wanted to flesh out the low poly source art,

378
00:19:42,468 --> 00:19:46,090
we needed to consider where we should pull our character

379
00:19:46,110 --> 00:19:47,130
design influence from.

380
00:19:48,631 --> 00:19:50,892
At first, we flirted with the simple idea

381
00:19:50,912 --> 00:19:52,733
of taking inspiration from original concept art,

382
00:19:53,093 --> 00:19:55,314
from toys, costumes, later era models,

383
00:19:56,054 --> 00:19:58,775
things that were already more fleshed out and detailed

384
00:19:58,935 --> 00:19:59,736
than 32-bit games.

385
00:20:01,656 --> 00:20:03,397
While this would make sense, seem

386
00:20:03,417 --> 00:20:05,058
to make sense while targeting a higher fidelity look,

387
00:20:08,473 --> 00:20:12,377
they really kind of diverged to a degree.

388
00:20:12,997 --> 00:20:14,999
While the various looks of Crash have commonalities,

389
00:20:15,719 --> 00:20:17,621
orange fur, blue shorts, spiky hair,

390
00:20:18,802 --> 00:20:20,783
people have particular opinions about which one

391
00:20:20,803 --> 00:20:22,004
they might personally want to see.

392
00:20:25,046 --> 00:20:26,888
The Crash band had been relatively dormant

393
00:20:27,648 --> 00:20:29,470
and the art style had changed over the years

394
00:20:29,990 --> 00:20:31,832
and this seemed to kind of cause a sense of confusion

395
00:20:31,872 --> 00:20:33,053
to a degree among the fan base.

396
00:20:34,254 --> 00:20:36,876
And we had to be mindful of what source we were pulling from.

397
00:20:38,263 --> 00:20:42,007
This is a discussion we had to have in regards to every character and all the assets in the

398
00:20:42,047 --> 00:20:42,307
game.

399
00:20:42,507 --> 00:20:47,031
Crash is just a kind of a clear good example of the variation that the brand experienced

400
00:20:47,071 --> 00:20:47,532
over the years.

401
00:20:49,894 --> 00:20:55,259
The conclusion is that we eventually came to is that these higher fidelity assets, marketing

402
00:20:55,279 --> 00:21:00,044
materials and stuff, is they lack the simplicity and direct lines of the PlayStation 1 art

403
00:21:00,484 --> 00:21:03,307
that most people were likely to be subconsciously responsive to.

404
00:21:04,661 --> 00:21:08,925
We tried to keep our ear to the ground and observe how people responded to different

405
00:21:08,945 --> 00:21:12,548
game remakes or how they had discussed our previous crash efforts.

406
00:21:13,409 --> 00:21:18,433
Our solution was to kind of preserve the essential angularity of the 32-bit models of the vintage

407
00:21:18,473 --> 00:21:23,938
look, get the character designs right by being faithful to classic looks the majority of

408
00:21:23,978 --> 00:21:29,402
audiences would have nostalgia for without actually creating low-poly art ourselves.

409
00:21:31,523 --> 00:21:37,364
When I say essential angularity, I tend to mean the major movements of the shape and silhouette.

410
00:21:38,144 --> 00:21:41,585
So these are the field people respond to on a kind of core level.

411
00:21:41,965 --> 00:21:47,306
So artists needed to not be selfish, had to let go of our previous styles and any desires

412
00:21:47,346 --> 00:21:49,527
to really heavily reinvent these characters.

413
00:21:50,267 --> 00:21:55,528
We kind of had to reverse engineer them back to their core, not over-design or fix them.

414
00:21:57,349 --> 00:21:59,169
These characters have a lot of appeal in their own way.

415
00:22:00,263 --> 00:22:03,544
we should polish and not try to lose that kind of core essence.

416
00:22:04,444 --> 00:22:09,846
For Krash himself, this meant keeping that basic triangular shape language that was essential.

417
00:22:11,147 --> 00:22:16,069
You know, preserve it because it's so easy to lose those kind of strong core primitive

418
00:22:16,109 --> 00:22:19,310
shapes when you want to be making art that feels modern and impressive.

419
00:22:20,010 --> 00:22:21,391
This is something we strove to keep in mind.

420
00:22:22,944 --> 00:22:25,405
which isn't to say we were completely literal all the time.

421
00:22:26,226 --> 00:22:28,427
You know, calls had to be made like fitting Crash's eyes

422
00:22:28,467 --> 00:22:29,807
a little bit better into his cranium,

423
00:22:30,428 --> 00:22:32,109
kind of giving him more structural integrity,

424
00:22:32,509 --> 00:22:34,770
kind of more flexibility for animation and consistency.

425
00:22:37,551 --> 00:22:40,133
You can see this approach here applied on entropy as well.

426
00:22:41,173 --> 00:22:42,594
The old model and the new model,

427
00:22:43,134 --> 00:22:46,436
just kind of being mindful of certain shape regions

428
00:22:46,636 --> 00:22:48,517
and the relative relationship they have,

429
00:22:48,637 --> 00:22:51,698
even during pretty noticeable squash and stretch.

430
00:22:54,537 --> 00:22:57,879
So kind of moving on from what worked to when there were complications for us.

431
00:22:59,120 --> 00:23:03,722
We found eventually that individual perception of the retro graphics could cause disagreement.

432
00:23:04,603 --> 00:23:09,026
Definitely among the fan base and even among artists working on a given task.

433
00:23:09,850 --> 00:23:12,692
You know, there's only so much fidelity that was visible to most people playing these games

434
00:23:12,732 --> 00:23:15,493
in the first place over composite cables on their CRT TV.

435
00:23:16,654 --> 00:23:20,155
Videos an artist might be referencing might have been captured at a low resolution.

436
00:23:21,136 --> 00:23:24,338
It can lead to a lack of clarity over what some characters' prop pieces were.

437
00:23:25,838 --> 00:23:29,680
As a kid, I remember trying to look through my TV screen, trying to get past the color

438
00:23:29,700 --> 00:23:33,082
bleed of the CRT, you know, trying to see the pixels of the characters more clearly.

