686
00:36:32,361 --> 00:36:33,282
problems in authoring.

687
00:36:34,042 --> 00:36:37,024
Alignment between animation components and animation slots

688
00:36:37,084 --> 00:36:37,965
became problematic.

689
00:36:38,565 --> 00:36:40,146
And Flash really pooped its pants

690
00:36:40,206 --> 00:36:42,148
when high-res pre-rendered 3D frames

691
00:36:42,328 --> 00:36:43,368
needed to be incorporated.

692
00:36:44,209 --> 00:36:46,731
Granted, by introducing high-resolution raster images,

693
00:36:47,271 --> 00:36:49,593
we pushed Flash in a way that it wasn't meant to be pushed.

694
00:36:50,420 --> 00:36:51,801
But we were too far into production

695
00:36:51,921 --> 00:36:53,362
to make changes in authoring tools.

696
00:36:53,882 --> 00:36:55,642
Instead, more resources had to be put

697
00:36:55,682 --> 00:36:58,283
into existing animation pipelines to shore it up.

698
00:37:00,604 --> 00:37:02,165
For cut scenes, we went with Premiere,

699
00:37:02,545 --> 00:37:04,046
primarily because we're familiar with it,

700
00:37:04,566 --> 00:37:07,887
but automating Premiere for cut scene rendering

701
00:37:08,127 --> 00:37:10,448
proved to be challenging in the time frame that we had.

702
00:37:11,433 --> 00:37:16,377
Thus, since every tweak, bug, or polish pass required a cutscene to be reprocessed

703
00:37:16,557 --> 00:37:20,940
through a fairly complex export cycle, we ultimately poured a lot of resources into

704
00:37:21,361 --> 00:37:28,386
managing and maintaining that pipeline. So while new tools are more powerful, you're

705
00:37:28,426 --> 00:37:32,129
